white has traded a B and N for a R and P. even though the point counter deems the trade even, white is now down a piece, under-developed (the only active piece is currently pinned), and uncastled. Making matters even more worrisome for white is that black is already in the position of trading even pieces, further emphasizing white's trade. 
 
And lastly, as an advisement against such a trade...with the amount of pawns still on the board, and the lack of open lanes, the Bs and Ns are more useful at this stage of the game than Rs. So white essentially traded away 2 good pieces for 1 bad piece.
